The function `UnusedSubroutineSearchAmsiPattern` should implement a pattern search algorithm to find the starting address of the matched pattern within the given memory range. One common algorithm is the Rabin-Karp algorithm, which can be used for this purpose. Here's an example implementation of the Rabin-Karp algorithm in C++:

```cpp
ULONGLONG UnusedSubroutineSearchAmsiPattern(PBYTE Address, DWORD Size, PBYTE Pattern, DWORD PatternSize)
{
    ULONGLONG hashPattern = 0;
    ULONGLONG hashCurrent = 0;
    ULONGLONG h = 1;
    int i, j;

    // Calculate the hash value of the pattern
    for (i = 0; i < PatternSize - 1; i++)
        h = (h * 256) % Q;

    // Calculate the hash value of the first window of text
    for (i = 0; i < PatternSize; i++)
    {
        hashPattern = (256 * hashPattern + Pattern[i]) % Q;
        hashCurrent = (256 * hashCurrent + Address[i]) % Q;
    }

    // Slide the pattern over the text one by one
    for (i = 0; i <= Size - PatternSize; i++)
    {
        // Check the hash values of current window of text and pattern
        // If the hash values match then only check for characters on by one
        if (hashPattern == hashCurrent)
        {
            for (j = 0; j < PatternSize; j++)
            {
                if (Address[i + j]!= Pattern[j])
                    break;
            }

            // if p[0...M-1] = t[i, i+1,...i+M-1]
            if (j == PatternSize)
                return i; // found
        }

        // Calculate hash value for next window of text: Remove leading digit, add trailing digit
        if (i < Size - PatternSize)
        {
            hashCurrent = (256 * (hashCurrent - Address[i] * h) + Address[i + PatternSize]) % Q;

            // We might get negative value of hashCurrent, converting it to positive
            if (hashCurrent < 0)
                hashCurrent = (hashCurrent + Q);
        }
    }

    return 0; // not found
}
```

Please note that the variable `Q` should be a prime number greater than the number of elements in the pattern and the text. This implementation assumes that `Q` is a prime number.

Also, this code does not handle wildcard characters in the pattern. If you need to handle wildcards, you would need to modify the code accordingly.

